The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, June 23: After approving a $2-billion grant last year, the World Bank today said it was discussing with India for another $1-billion (about Rs 4,500 crore) credit to help shore up capital of its public sector banks. Discussions are going on with the Indian government to provide another $1 billion for bank recapitalisation, World Bank country director for India Roberto Zagha said.                            
	 New Delhi, June 23: The last day for submission of bids for the 4,000MW mega power project at Sarguja in Chhattisgarh may be extended by two months as the plan awaits clearance from the ministry of environment and forests.                            
	 Mumbai, June 23: Taking a step towards a possible stake sale to US-based TPG, debt-ridden Vishal Retail today said its board had approved the terms of a memorandum of understanding with the private equity firm in accordance with a debt rejig programme approved by its lenders.                            
	 New Delhi, June 23: Tata Motors plans to raise long-term funds to restructure its over Rs 18,500-crore debt, for which a board meeting has been called on Monday. Sources said the company planned to cut down its debt substantially and would evaluate various ways to raise funds.                            
	 New Delhi, June 23: Hyundai Motor India expects its domestic sales to grow about 15 per cent on account of a revival in the auto market. The company today launched an advanced version of the Verna, priced at Rs 6.56 lakh-Rs 9.22 lakh (ex showroom Delhi).                            
	 New York, June 23: Indias population of high net worth individuals grew 51 per cent to over 1.26 lakh in 2009, riding on the surge in market valuations and improved economic growth.                            
	 New Delhi, June 23: Smoking and excessive drinking by employees was resulting in an annual loss of about Rs 700-800 crore for companies, a study by industry association Assocham said.                                                                                                                          
